        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>A LINE transposon is a stretch of DNA that can copy and reinsert itself elsewhere within a genome. In humans, transposons of the LINE family are unusually active in the hippocampus, a brain region closely tied to learning, memory, and other forms of complex thought. Most transposons, over the long ages, become corrupted and fall permanently silent, but those of the LINE family have somehow stayed active in the genomes of a select few animals. When researchers sequencing the genome of a famously intelligent octopus species detected an active LINE transposon of the very same family, they proposed a bold hypothesis: that this particular family of transposons is somehow bound up with the capacity for advanced cognition not just in humans but across the animal kingdom more broadly.</p>",
