        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>Paleontologists working in one region recently reported the discovery of some very old fossils and argued that certain other fossils, of a similar age but found at two separate sites elsewhere, have been misidentified. Many researchers had taken those other fossils to be the remains of jellyfish, largely on the strength of features that look like trailing tentacles. The question is far from trivial, since a firm identification of the disputed fossils as jellyfish would push the earliest known appearance of the group back by many millions of years. The paleontologists disagree: those apparent tentacles, they contend, are really the comb-rows of a different and only distantly related animal, so the fossils are not jellyfish at all but the remains of that other creature.</p>",
