        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>Researchers studying a burrowing owl, a small owl that nests in tunnels dug into open ground, noticed a curious habit: the owls collect animal dung and use it to line the entrances of their burrows. Lining a burrow with dung is a slow and repetitive chore, one the owls carry out again and again, which suggested to the researchers that the habit must bring the birds some real benefit. The researchers proposed an explanation. Dung, they knew, draws dung beetles, which the owls happen to relish, so the researchers hypothesized that lining the burrow with dung is really a clever way for the owl to lure its favorite prey right to its own doorstep, rather than having to range widely in search of it.</p>",
