        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<figure style='margin:0 0 14px'><figcaption style='font-weight:600;text-align:center;margin-bottom:8px;font-size:14px'>Two Alloys' Strength and Density</figcaption><table style='border-collapse:collapse;margin:0 auto;line-height:1.3'><thead><tr><th style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;background:rgba(127,127,127,0.14);font-weight:600;font-size:13px'>Alloy</th><th style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;background:rgba(127,127,127,0.14);font-weight:600;font-size:13px'>Strength (MPa)</th><th style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;background:rgba(127,127,127,0.14);font-weight:600;font-size:13px'>Density (g/cm3)</th><th style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;background:rgba(127,127,127,0.14);font-weight:600;font-size:13px'>Strength per density</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:left'>Alloy X</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>600</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>7.5</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>80</td></tr><tr><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:left'>Alloy Y</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>500</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>5.0</td><td style='border:1px solid currentColor;padding:5px 9px;font-size:13px;text-align:center'>100</td></tr></tbody></table></figure><p>Engineers choosing a metal for aircraft parts care less about raw strength than about the ratio of strength to density, since a part that is strong but heavy is of little use in the air. Comparing two candidate alloys, the engineers recorded for each its strength, its density, and its strength-to-density ratio. Noting that Alloy X is, in absolute terms, the stronger of the two metals, the engineers went on to point out that, for the particular demands of aircraft, Alloy Y ______</p>",
