        passage: "<p>A historian argues that the rapid growth of a certain medieval city was driven, above all, by a change in the farming of the surrounding countryside, a change that freed many people from the land and allowed them to move into the city, rather than by any expansion of the city's own trade with the outside world. For centuries the region's fields had been worked, acre by acre, by nearly everyone who lived there, leaving very few hands free to take up any other kind of work at all. To support this argument, the historian points to a range of surviving records from the decades in question.</p>",
