        id: "qb-coe-122",
        domain: "Information & Ideas",
        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>Studying a species of orb-weaving spider, researchers noticed that females which had recently fed well went on to spin distinctly larger webs than females which had fed only poorly. A female orb-weaver takes down and rebuilds her web almost every day, and spinning a new one is costly, so the size of her web at any given moment closely tracks how much energy she has lately had to spare. This led the researchers to a hypothesis about what those webs communicate: that the size of a female's web is an honest signal of how well she has recently eaten, so that a large web serves, in effect, to advertise a well-fed female to any males that come looking for a mate.</p>",
