        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>A researcher claims that a newly unearthed cache of stone tools was made by one particular ancient culture, resting the claim on the tools' distinctive shape. A colleague pushes back: shape alone, she argues, cannot settle the matter, since a neighboring culture is known to have made tools of a very similar shape at around the same time. The distinctive shape of a set of stone tools is often the surest clue an archaeologist has to which ancient culture once occupied a site, which is exactly why the shape carries so much weight in this dispute. The researcher, however, maintains that a further line of evidence puts the identification beyond reasonable doubt.</p>",
