        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>An astronomer claims that the regular dimming of a distant star is caused by a large planet that passes in front of the star at fixed intervals, briefly blocking part of its light. A colleague disputes this, arguing that the dimming comes instead from dark patches on the star's own surface, which grow darker and then fade as the star slowly rotates them into and out of view. The astronomer, however, maintains that the precise pattern of the dimming favors a planet over surface patches.</p>",
