        domain: "Information & Ideas",
        skill: "Command of Evidence",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p>A certain bat hunts flying insects deep within cluttered forest, an environment where the echoes bouncing back from countless leaves and branches could easily drown out the echo of a small insect. Most bats hunt by giving off rapid pulses of sound and listening for the echoes that come back, a method that grows far harder to use in a place where echoes come crowding back from every side at once. Researchers studying the bat proposed that it copes with all this clutter by calling at a higher pitch than its relatives that hunt out in the open air, reasoning that higher-pitched calls yield sharper, more finely detailed echoes from small objects, and so help the forest bat pick its prey out from the surrounding tangle.</p>",
