        passage: "<p>A geologist claims that a certain wide, flat plain was shaped, long ago, by a vast lake that has since entirely vanished. A colleague counters that the plain was instead shaped by a broad, slow-moving river. A standing lake and a flowing river leave behind very different traces in the ground, and telling the two apart, long after the water itself has gone, is a familiar sort of challenge for geologists. The geologist holds firm, maintaining that certain features of the plain point clearly to a standing lake rather than to a flowing river.</p>",
