        difficulty: "medium",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Archaeologist Dr. Rosa Iglesias argues that an ancient circle of standing stones was built to track the sun. On the longest day of each year, she notes, the sunrise lines up exactly with the largest of the stones. Such precise alignment, in her view, could not be mere accident. For Iglesias, the circle was above all a great calendar of the sun.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Nils Eriksson found that the same circle also aligns neatly with the rising of a particular bright star at a certain season. He argues that the builders may well have watched the stars as much as the sun from within the ring of stones. A single circle, he notes, can be aimed at more than one light in the sky. The builders, in his view, may have tracked the heavens far more widely than the sun alone.</p>",
