        domain: "Craft & Structure",
        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>The use of nanohybrids—materials formed by joining two different nanomaterials—has raced ahead of any careful study of their risks. Researchers now build these composites far faster than anyone can test how safe they really are. <u>Because joining can alter a material's properties, a risk estimate based on the separate ingredients may badly understate the danger of the combined nanohybrid.</u> Two perfectly harmless nanomaterials, in other words, might form a hybrid that is anything but harmless. To judge a nanohybrid by its parts alone, on this view, is to risk a dangerous surprise.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>The heightened toxicity that some nanohybrids show relative to their ingredients certainly deserves attention, but the effect of joining varies a great deal from one case to the next. In one recent study, joining zinc oxide with silicon dioxide preserved the useful transparency of the zinc oxide while sharply reducing its tendency to damage DNA. The combination, in that instance, turned out to be far safer than one of its parts had been alone. Joining does not always add danger, the author stresses, and can in fact sometimes take it away. Each new hybrid, on this view, has to be judged carefully on its own.</p>",
        prompt: "Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the assertion in the underlined portion of Text 1?",
