        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Geneticist Dr. Ada Whitfield argues that a fish's unusual resistance to a toxin is inherited through a single gene. Fish carrying one particular version of the gene survive in the polluted water, she reports, while those without it quickly die. She points to a clean, sharp divide between the survivors and the rest. One gene, in her view, draws the line between life and death in these waters. For Whitfield, the resistance has a single, simple genetic cause.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Ravi Chaudhary sequenced resistant fish drawn from several different rivers and found that the various populations resist the same toxin through changes in several different genes. He argues that the resistance evolved more than once, by more than one genetic route. In one river the fish lean on one gene, he notes, and in another they rely on quite a different one. What looks like a single trait, in his view, has arisen again and again along separate paths. The resistance, he concludes, is not the work of one gene but of many.</p>",
