        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Studying an early farming society, Dr. Elena Costa argues that its people prospered chiefly because they irrigated their fields from a nearby river. The steady water supply, she claims, let them harvest far more grain than rain-fed farmers ever could. Their canals and ditches, in her view, were the foundation of their wealth. Control the water, she reasons, and a society can feed a growing population. For Costa, irrigation alone explains the society's success.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Amir Haddad found that the society's storage pits held wild seeds and animal bones lying right alongside the cultivated grain. He argues that these farmers leaned heavily on hunting and gathering as well, and that irrigation was only one part of how they fed themselves. A people who stored acorns and hunted deer, he notes, were not living on grain alone. Their prosperity, in his view, rested on several sources of food at once. To credit the river alone, he concludes, is to miss half the story.</p>",
