        domain: "Craft & Structure",
        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Physicist Dr. Nadia Rahman argues that a particle has no definite position at all until the moment it is measured. The very act of measurement, she claims, is what forces the particle to take on a single, definite location. Before that instant, in her view, the particle is spread across many possibilities at once. Nothing about its place is settled, she insists, until an observer looks. For Rahman, measurement does not find a position but creates one.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Klaus Berger proposes instead that the particle always has a perfectly definite position, though one that stays hidden from us until we measure it. On his view, a measurement simply reveals a location that had existed all along rather than conjuring it into being. The particle is somewhere real, he insists, whether or not anyone is watching. Our ignorance before the measurement, in his view, is a fact about us and not about the particle. For Berger, the position is discovered, not made.</p>",
