        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Some biologists argue that life on Earth first began at the deep-sea hydrothermal vents, where hot, mineral-rich water meets the cold seawater. At such vents, sharp differences in chemistry pile up across a very short distance. <u>The steep chemical gradients at these vents, they claim, could have supplied the energy needed to assemble the first living molecules.</u> Such an energy source, in their view, might have driven simple chemicals to link into something alive. The vents, on this account, were the cradle of life itself.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Sofia Marchetti notes that the earliest known cells used chemistry strikingly similar to the very reactions that still occur at such vents today. That resemblance, she agrees, is genuinely suggestive and hard to dismiss. Still, she cautions firmly that a resemblance is not the same thing as a proof. No one, she points out, has yet managed to build a single living cell from vent chemistry in the laboratory. Until someone does, in her view, the idea remains a promising hypothesis rather than an established fact.</p>",
