        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Linguist Dr. Marta Vidal reconstructs an ancient parent language and argues that its speakers had a single word meaning both 'snow' and 'ice.' The descendant languages, she notes, all use closely related words for the two things. That shared root, in her view, points back to one word in the parent tongue. Where the daughters agree so closely, she reasons, the mother likely spoke of snow and ice as one. For Vidal, the single word is the simplest explanation of the pattern.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Owen Fletcher points out that in several of those very descendant languages, the words for snow and for ice, though similar, are in fact clearly distinct from each other. He argues that the parent language, too, may well have kept the two ideas apart in two separate words. Closely related words, he notes, need not descend from a single shared one. The daughters may simply have inherited a pair that was always a pair. For Fletcher, the evidence points to two ancestral words rather than one.</p>",
