        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Studying early metalworking in the Caucasus, Dr. Kamran Aliyev argues that the region's smiths learned to work bronze from their neighbors to the south. The technique, he claims, spread steadily northward into the Caucasus along the established trade routes. As traders moved, in his view, so did the knowledge of how to alloy and cast bronze. The skill arrived from elsewhere, he reasons, carried in with the caravans. For Aliyev, Caucasus bronze-working was borrowed rather than invented.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Leyla Guliyeva analyzed the chemical signatures of the local bronzes and found recipes quite unlike those used in the lands to the south. She argues that the Caucasus smiths may well have developed their bronze-working independently, drawing on the region's own distinctive ores. A borrowed technique, she notes, would have carried a borrowed recipe with it. Instead the local mixtures look homegrown, matching the metals of the surrounding hills. For Guliyeva, the craft may have been discovered in the Caucasus itself.</p>",
