        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Immunologist Dr. Hana Okafor argues that a vaccine works by exposing the immune system to a weakened form of a germ, prompting the body to build up its defenses. On any later exposure to the real germ, she notes, those defenses respond at once. The body, in her view, learns from a safe rehearsal with a crippled invader. Show it a harmless version now, she reasons, and it will be ready for the dangerous one later. For Okafor, a vaccine is above all a controlled introduction to the germ itself.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Daniel Weiss studies newer vaccines that contain no germ at all, but only a set of instructions that lead the body's own cells to make a single harmless piece of the germ. The immune system, he explains, learns to recognize that one piece just as well as it would a whole weakened germ. No invader, weakened or otherwise, ever enters the body. The lesson is taught, in his view, using only a blueprint and the body's own machinery. For Weiss, a vaccine need not contain any germ to do its work.</p>",
