        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Economist Dr. Sara Nkosi argues that a city grows wealthy chiefly because its dense population lets workers and firms exchange ideas quickly. When people are packed close together, she claims, knowledge spreads fast and new ventures multiply. Proximity, in her view, is the true engine of a city's prosperity. Crowd talented people into a small space, she reasons, and invention follows. For Nkosi, it is density above all that makes a city rich.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Tariq Rahman found that some sprawling, low-density cities have prospered every bit as much as the dense ones, by investing heavily in fast transport and communication. He argues that easy connection, however it is achieved, matters far more than sheer density itself. A spread-out city with good roads and networks, he notes, can exchange ideas as quickly as a crowded one. What counts, in his view, is the flow of ideas rather than the closeness of bodies. For Rahman, connection, not density, is the real key.</p>",
