        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Materials scientist Dr. Priya Nair reports that a new kind of concrete heals its own cracks because bacteria mixed into it produce limestone whenever water seeps in. The bacteria, she notes, lie dormant deep in the dry concrete until a crack finally lets moisture reach them. Once awakened, they set to work sealing the gap with fresh stone. The living concrete, in her view, repairs itself without any human help. For Nair, the secret of the self-healing lies in the sleeping bacteria.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Lars Eriksson has developed a quite different self-healing concrete that contains no bacteria at all, only tiny capsules of glue that burst open the moment a crack begins to form. Both approaches, he notes, manage to seal a crack before water can ever reach and rust the steel reinforcing bars inside. His capsules do with chemistry, he explains, what Nair's microbes do with life. The two recipes are unalike, in his view, but they share the same goal. For Eriksson, there is more than one way to make concrete mend itself.</p>",
