        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Astrophysicist Dr. Chen Liu argues that a neutron star's interior is made simply of ordinary neutrons packed together to an enormous density. The star's carefully measured mass and size, he claims, fit this straightforward picture very well. There is no need, in his view, to imagine anything stranger inside. The plain neutron model, he reasons, already accounts for what the telescopes see. For Liu, a neutron star is exactly what its name suggests.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Amara Diallo notes that a few neutron stars appear to be slightly smaller than the neutron model predicts for their particular mass. She argues that the cores of those stars may contain exotic matter, denser even than tightly packed neutrons, that the simple model leaves out entirely. A star squeezed smaller than neutrons allow, she reasons, must hold something stranger within. The tidy model works for most, in her view, but not quite for all. For Diallo, the oddest stars hint at physics still unknown.</p>",
