        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Microbiologist Dr. Hana Okafor argues that bacteria become resistant to an antibiotic only after the drug has been introduced, as the chance mutations that happen to survive it slowly spread. Resistance, she claims, is fundamentally a response to the drug's arrival. Before the antibiotic appears, in her view, there is simply nothing for resistance to respond to. Introduce the drug, she reasons, and only then does resistance begin to build. For Okafor, the drug itself calls the resistance into being.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Daniel Weiss revived bacteria that had been frozen for decades, long before the antibiotic was ever used, and found that a few of them already carried resistance genes. He argues that resistance can therefore exist within a population well before the drug ever appears, lying ready to spread the moment it does. Those frozen microbes, he points out, had never once met the antibiotic. Resistance was waiting in the wings, in his view, not created on cue. For Weiss, the trait can long predate the drug that favors it.</p>",
