        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Marine chemist Dr. Sofia Marchetti argues that ocean acidification will gradually dissolve the shells of sea snails, since more acidic water slowly eats away at their chalky shells. Rising acidity, she warns, threatens very nearly all shelled sea life. A shell of chalk, in her view, simply cannot withstand a steadily souring sea. As the water grows more acidic, she reasons, the shells thin and fail. For Marchetti, acidification spells danger for every shelled creature.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Rahul Mehta found that some snails living in naturally acidic waters actually build thicker shells and grow a protective outer layer that resists the dissolving. He argues that certain species may in fact adapt to the acidification rather than simply succumbing to it. Where the water has long been sour, he notes, the snails have already learned to cope. Not every shelled creature, in his view, is helpless before the change. For Mehta, some species will bend rather than break.</p>",
