        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Dendrochronologist Dr. Bao Zhang argues that wide tree rings in a given year mark a warm growing season, while narrow rings mark a cold one. Warmth, in his view, lets a tree grow freely and lay down a broad ring. He uses centuries of stacked rings to reconstruct a whole region's past temperatures. Read the widths in order, he reasons, and the climate of long-ago summers appears. For Zhang, ring width is a faithful record of past warmth.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Freya Nilsen found that in dry regions, ring width actually tracks the rainfall far more closely than the temperature, since it is water, and not warmth, that limits the trees' growth there. She argues that ring width therefore means quite different things in different climates. In a parched land, she explains, a wide ring records a wet year rather than a warm one. To read every ring as a thermometer, in her view, is to misread the dry ones badly. For Nilsen, the meaning of a ring depends on where the tree grew.</p>",
