        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Ornithologist Dr. Ruby Chandra argues that a bird's blue-green egg color evolved in order to hide the eggs from predators against a background of green leaves. The color, she claims, is essentially camouflage. Tucked among the foliage, in her view, a blue-green egg simply disappears from a hungry eye. Blend the egg into the leaves, she reasons, and fewer are ever found. For Chandra, the color is a disguise and nothing more.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Owen Fletcher found that the very same pigment also shields the developing chick within from harmful sunlight, and that eggs laid in sunnier nests are noticeably more deeply colored. He argues that the color may therefore guard against the sunlight rather than, or as well as, hiding the egg from predators. A deeper shade where the sun beats down, he notes, looks far more like a sunscreen than a disguise. The pigment may protect the chick, in his view, not just conceal it. For Fletcher, the color does more than hide.</p>",
