        skill: "Cross-Text Connections",
        difficulty: "hard",
        passage: "<p><b>Text 1</b><br>Archaeometallurgist Dr. Sofia Bruno argues that early smiths hardened their copper tools simply by hammering them while cold, a process that packs the soft metal tightly together. The tools' dense, worked edges, she notes, plainly show the marks of that hammering. Cold blows, in her view, were the whole secret of a hard copper edge. Beat the metal firmly, she reasons, and it hardens under the hammer. For Bruno, the hardness was won by hammering alone.</p><p><b>Text 2</b><br>Dr. Henrik Adler found that some of those very same tools also contain a faint trace of arsenic, a metal that hardens copper considerably when it is melted in together with it. He agrees that the smiths did indeed hammer their tools but adds that they clearly also alloyed the copper deliberately to make it harder still. The arsenic, he explains, could not have wandered in by chance. The smiths used two tricks at once, in his view, not merely the one. For Adler, hammering was only half of their craft.</p>",
